13th of January, and old &s;tile for ever.</P>
<P><HI>Jargon grav'd, &amp;c.</HI>] JARGON is here properly introduced graving our hero's titles, which are admirably brought into ver&s;e&punc; but the gentleman who wrote the la&s;t note, Mr. Orator H&mdash;ley, takes umbrage at this pa&s;&s;age, and exclaimeth to the following effect. &startq;Jargon is meant for me.&endq; There is more mu&s;ic in a peal of marrowbones and cleavers than in the&s;e ver&s;es.&mdash;I am a logician upon fundamentals.&mdash;Arationali&s;t,&mdash;lover of <HI>mankande,</HI> Gla&s;tonberry thorn.-r-huzza, boys.&mdash;Wit a vivacious command of all objects and ideas.&mdash;I am the only wit in Great Britain. See Oratory tracts, &amp;c. 10036.&endq;</P>
<P>Patience, good Mr. Q$ator! We are not at lei&s;ure to an&s;wer thee at pre&s;ent, but mu&s;t ob&s;erve that <HI>Jargon</HI> has done more for our hero, than ever did the &s;ociety at Bordeaux, as will ap|pear from the following extract of a letter &s;ent to MARTINUS MACULARIUS, by a fellow of that &s;ociety:</P>
<P>J$ai bitn re&ccedil;u la le$tre, dont vous m'a$ez fait l'honneur le $ame pa&s;s&eacute;. A e'gard de ce Mon&s;ieur Hillario, qui &s;e vante &s;i prodigien&s;ement chez vous, je ne trouve pas qu'il e&s;t enroll&eacute; dans no$$e foci&eacute; &eacute; &amp; &s;o$ nom e&s;t parfaitment inconnu ici&punc; J'attends $e vous nouvelles, &amp;c.</P>
