<P><HI>A paltry Play'r, &amp;c.]</HI> It appears that the fir&s;t effort of this univer&s;al genius, who is lately become remarkable as the Bo|badil of literature, was to excell in Pantomime. What was the event?&mdash;he was damned.&mdash;Mr. Cro&s;s, the prompter, took great pains to fit him for the part of Oroonoko&mdash;he was damned.&mdash;He attempted Captain Blandford&mdash;he was damned.&mdash;He acted Con&s;tant in the Provok'd Wife&mdash;he was damned.&mdash;He repre&s;ented the Botani&s;t in Romeo and Juliet, at the Little.</P>
<P>T$eatre in the Hay-market, under the direction of Mr. The. Cibber&mdash;he was damned.&mdash;He appeared in the character of Lothario, at the celebrated theatre in May-Fair&mdash;he was damned there too. Mr. Cro&s;s, however, to alleviate his misfortune, charitably be&s;towed upon him a 15th part of his own benefit. See the Gentleman's Magazine for la&s;t December, and al&s;o Woodward's letter, pa&s;&s;im.</P>
<P><HI>No mortal read.]</HI> Notwith&s;tanding this a&s;&s;ertion of Momus, our hero pro e&acirc;, qu&acirc; e&s;t, verecunda&igrave;, compareth him&s;elf to Addi&s;on and Steele, which occa&s;ioned the following epigram, by the right hon. the $arl * * * addre&s;&s;ed to the right ho|nourable G&mdash;e D&mdash;n.</P>
