<DIV1>
<PB N="229" REF="257">
<HEAD>ODE to a Virginia Nightingale, which was cured of
a Fit in the Bo&s;om of a young Lady, who after|wards
nur&s;ed the Author in a dangerous Illne&s;s.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>Sweet bird! who&s;e fate and mine agree,</L>
<L>As far as proud humanity,</L>
<L>The parallel will own;</L>
<L>O let our voice and hearts combine,</L>
<L>O let us, wow-warblers join,</L>
<L>Our patrone&s;s to crown.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>When heavy hung thy flagging wing,</L>
<L>When thou could'&s;t neither move nor &s;ing,</L>
<L>Of &s;pirits void and re&s;t;</L>
<L>A lovely nymph her aid apply'd,</L>
<L>She gave the bli&s;s to heav'n allied,</L>
<L>And cur'd thee on her brea&s;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Me too the kind indulgent maid,</L>
<L>With gen'rous care and timely aid,</L>
<L>Re&s;tor'd to mirth and health;</L>
<L>Then join'd to her, O may I prove</L>
<L>By friend&s;hip, gratitude, and love,</L>
<L>The Poverty of Wealth.</L>
</LG>
